Screenshot attached.

If the timezone of a calendar is changed to one covered by the daylight savings, the calendar displays a wrong set of events in the months that the changes occur.

*Steps to reproduce*
# Create a calendar with a timezone like America/New York (-0400), for example;
# Set some recurring weekly events on it (Calendar1.png);
# Create a subscription for this Calendar;
# Rearrange the events on the Calendar by moving them to different days (Calendar2.png);
# Change the timezone to America/Sao Paulo (-0200).

*Expected behavior*
Nothing changes besides the timezone.

*Actual behavior*
The events on the Calendar are rearranged and some of them are now displayed incorrectly (Calendar3.png).
At this point, if you start changing the order of events again, all the Calendar *subscriptions* will show what it seems to be an out of sync content.
Even if you were to revert the timezone setting back, the Calendar subscriptions won't get fixed, nor will the Calendar on Confluence.

h3. Step to reproduce: 
# Create around 100 calendar and having around 10k of restriction setting for the calendar.
# Create the subscription link for each calendar
# Use the calendar client to fire the subscription request to team Calendar frequently.

h3. Current behaviour: 
We can observe that the heap usage on Confluence is having peak on almost each request, which trigger the full GC frequently. 

h3. Root cause: 
From the database record, it seems that team calendar is retrieving the entirety of users and groups that are used to restrict any calendar, rather than just the specific user/groups relevant to the calendar at hand:
{code}
SELECT GROUP_NAME,TYPE,SUB_CALENDAR_ID,ID FROM AO_950DC3_TC_SUBCALS_PRIV_GRP;
SELECT SUB_CALENDAR_ID,TYPE,ID,USER_KEY FROM AO_950DC3_TC_SUBCALS_PRIV_USR;
{code}

